{
  "text": "While our knowledge of some of the molecular mechanisms involved in the control of var gene expression is accumulating rapidly, we still have very little understanding of how these processes are coordinated at the whole cell and population level in a way which provides the parasite with maximum potential to evade the immune response. We have previously proposed that structuring of parasite populations such that individual variants are only expressed one at a time might be achieved by short-lived cross-reacting antibody responses against epitopes shared between subsets of individual variants [CITATION_1] . However, early infection kinetics will not be affected by these adaptive immune responses and some additional, intrinsic control might therefore be require at this stage.",
